Q3: Unified Memory Manager — Dynamic Allocation
Spark uses a soft boundary between Execution and Storage memory. Both share the Unified Memory pool (60% of JVM heap minus 300MB reserved)

Scenario 1: NORMAL — Both have enough
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Execution Memory  │ Storage Memory │
│       50%          │     50%        │
│                    │  (cached DFs)  │
├────────────────────┤────────────────┤
│          Soft Boundary              │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘

Scenario 2: Execution needs MORE → evicts cached data (LRU)
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Execution Memory ──────►│ Storage  │
│       70%                │   30%    │
│  (borrows from storage)  │ (evicted)│
│                          │  LRU     │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘
  Storage data evicted using Least Recently Used

Scenario 3: Execution STILL not enough → Spill to Disk
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Execution Memory ──────────────►│S │
│       90%                        │10│
│  Still not enough? SPILL TO DISK │  │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘
         │
         ▼
  ┌──────────────┐
  │  Local Disk  │  (shuffle spill)
  └──────────────┘
Key Rules:

Execution can evict storage (cached data) using LRU
Storage cannot evict execution memory
If execution still isn't enough → spill to disk
Cached DFs getting evicted = jobs slow down (re-computation needed)


