            agg_funcs[func_name](F.col(col_name)).alias(f"{func_name}_{col_name}")
        )

# Apply
df = spark.table("sales_table")
result = df.groupBy("region").agg(*agg_exprs)
result.show()

Benefit: Just update agg_config dict — no SQL/code rewrite needed.

Q16: Deletion Vectors in Delta Lake
Traditional Delete: Rewrites entire Parquet files even to remove 1 row.

Deletion Vectors: Mark rows as deleted in a separate small file — no data files rewritten.
TRADITIONAL DELETE:                    WITH DELETION VECTORS:

┌──────────┐                          ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────────┐
│ Parquet1 │  ─── rewrite ──►  new    │ Parquet1 │  │ DeletionVec  │
│ 100 rows │       entire file        │ 100 rows │  │              │
│ delete 2 │                          │(untouched│  │ rows: [5,23] │
└──────────┘                          └──────────┘  │ (bitmap)     │
┌──────────┐                          ┌──────────┐  │              │
│ Parquet2 │  ─── rewrite ──►  new    │ Parquet2 │  │ rows: [7]    │
│ 100 rows │       entire file        │(untouched│  └──────────────┘
│ delete 1 │                          └──────────┘
└──────────┘                           
                                      Read time: Parquet files are
Cost: Rewrite GBs of data            read but deleted rows are
      for deleting few rows           SKIPPED using the bitmap
      Very slow & expensive           
                                      PURGE later: OPTIMIZE merges
                                      deletion vectors permanently

How it works under the hood:

DELETE writes a small deletion vector file (bitmap) — not rewriting data
On read, Spark checks the bitmap and skips deleted rows
Periodically, OPTIMIZE or PURGE physically removes deleted rows (compaction)


-- Enable deletion vectors
ALTER TABLE my_table SET TBLPROPERTIES ('delta.enableDeletionVectors' = true);

-- Delete is now fast (writes only deletion vector)
DELETE FROM my_table WHERE user_id = 12345;

-- Later, physically purge
OPTIMIZE my_table;
-- or
REORG TABLE my_table APPLY (PURGE);

Q17: Time Travel — Recover Accidentally Deleted Data

-- Step 1: Check table history to find version before the bad DELETE
DESCRIBE HISTORY my_table;
+-------+----------+---------------------+-----------+
|version|operation  |timestamp            |userName   |
+-------+----------+---------------------+-----------+
|   5   |DELETE     |2026-04-23 10:30:00  |you        |  ◄ BAD delete
|   4   |WRITE     |2026-04-23 09:00:00  |etl_job    |  ◄ GOOD state
|   3   |WRITE     |2026-04-22 09:00:00  |etl_job    |
+-------+----------+---------------------+-----------+

-- Step 2: Query the good version to verify
SELECT * FROM my_table VERSION AS OF 4;
-- or
SELECT * FROM my_table TIMESTAMP AS OF '2026-04-23 09:00:00';

-- Step 3: Restore the table
RESTORE TABLE my_table TO VERSION AS OF 4;
-- or
RESTORE TABLE my_table TO TIMESTAMP AS OF '2026-04-23 09:00:00';

# PySpark equivalent
df = spark.read.format("delta").option("versionAsOf", 4).table("my_table")

# Or restore
from delta.tables import DeltaTable
dt = DeltaTable.forName(spark, "my_table")
dt.restoreToVersion(4)

Key: Delta keeps history for 30 days by default (delta.logRetentionDuration). VACUUM removes old files, so don't VACUUM before restoring.

Q18: Liquid Clustering vs Traditional Partitioning
Problem with Partitioning:

Partitioned by date → but queries now filter on customer_id and region
Must drop + repartition = table rewrite (2-3 TB!)
High cardinality columns → thousands of tiny partitions → small file problem
Liquid Clustering:

No rigid folder structure
